children.subject:
If you have concerns I would contact the Registrar's office. Campus Scheduling is part of their office.

When voicing your concerns, please keep in mind that they, too, are doing their best but are understaffed and working with a finite quantity of classrooms.

A similar question was asked on another post but never received an answer: Who in the University should we voice our complaints to that CS classes are getting room assignments so late into the semester? Clearly you, the other advisors, and the EECS department are doing as much as they can. There must be someone we can voice our concerns to.

You should be able to put yourself on the wait list but it's doubtful you will get in. Sorry to be so brutal in sharing that news - we did the best we could to allocate the seats we had with too-great demand.
That's sad to hear...So it's impossible to get in even though I'm the 1st on the waitlist?
I wouldn't say impossible, but highly unlikely. I share this information in the spirit of giving you time to make other plans if you choose.
Thanks for the post. How about non-EECS grad students? Are we allowed to register for 289A at all?

At this point the enrollment system does NOT enforce pre-requisites. However, you should check with the instructor to make sure it's okay to bypass this class. Faculty do have the option to remove students from a class during the first two weeks if they don't meet the states prereqs.

The class is being taught in Pimentel in F19 which holds significantly fewer students than Wheeler and the class WILL NOT BE WEBCAST which means that enrollment will NOT expand past the levels indicated below.
The classes WILL use 999 sections for enrollment, they will NOT allow time conflicts. 
Total seats = 45 seats
     23 seats for CS & EECS grad students only
     22 seats set as permission code only but will be allocated for EECS MEng and managed by Michael Sun
